
**Role:** Audio / Music / Technical Audio  
**Project Type:** Team-based game development

---

## Project Overview

**Terminal Horizon** is a turn-based, grid-based cyberpunk roguelite where players control a team of three 'awakened simulants' attempting to escape a city citadel to see the sky before their time runs out.

This portfolio documents my learning, contributions, and reflections across the early development sprints, with a focus on **audio creation, technical implementation, collaboration, and professional growth**.

*(External project card: https://terminalhorizon.carrd.co)*

---

## Sprint 0 (Aug 10 - Aug 23)
### Induction & Prototyping

**[Aug 10] Induction**
The first day set the tone for the entire project. After meeting the team and reconnecting with familiar faces, the induction covered Playmakers’ structure, tools, pipelines, and expectations. The second half of the day shifted quickly into practice: temporary teams were formed and tasked with designing a prototype game under specific constraints.

Beyond the formal content, this day was valuable for networking and early relationship-building. Speaking directly with producers gave me a clearer sense of how decisions are made and what lies ahead. I made a conscious effort to engage widely and start building trust early - a decision I aimed to maintain throughout the project.

**[Aug 23] Prototype Presentations**  
Our temporary team pitched a bowling-inspired roguelite and presented a small playable demo. My contributions spanned multiple roles: music and sound, player systems programming (event bus and controller), writing parts of the GDD and pitch, and informal team management.

Managing people proved more complex than managing systems. Identifying who needed direction, information, or space required constant adjustment, but I enjoyed navigating that web. The experience, as it was intended, felt like a compressed version of a real development cycle, offering upfront, practical insight and preparing us for the start of the true project.

Only three of our six presented live, but the pitch went smoothly. A teammate overcame significant stage fright, which I found genuinely impressive. Our concept performed strongly in the poll, finishing close behind a prototype pitched by a more experienced developer and his team. Even though we placed second, the process itself felt like a win.

---

## Sprint 1 (Aug 24 - Sep 6)
### Game Selection & Skill Building

**[Aug 24] Game Chosen / First Audio Meeting**  
Although our prototype was popular, the steering committee went with the poll number one - the cyberpunk roguelite that would become *Terminal Horizon*. A standout moment was how quickly competition turned into shared excitement; regardless of outcome, the chosen game became everyone’s project.

The audio team formed: Quinn (composition and mastering), Chris (sound design), Nick (team lead) and myself (composition and audio implementation). Our first task focused on composition upskilling - recreating three reference tracks to match a predefined musical character. The exercise shed light on some kinks and rough spots in both areas of skill and communication for each of us, and adapting to that in stride was rewarding and brought the team closer. 

**[Aug 31] Halfway Review**  
I completed all three tracks early, though we reviewed only one per person. Feedback was largely positive, though Nick offered a critique I disagreed with - a small moment that foreshadowed future discussions around taste, intent, and justification.

*(Practice pieces: village theme, battle theme, eerie theme)*
