## Sprint 3 (Sep 21 - Oct 4)
### Writing for Systems, Not Ego

**[Sep 21] Team Meeting**  
Tasks moved from imitation to functionality: seamless looping, layering, and avoiding listener fatigue over long play sessions. My approach shifted toward systems thinking. We began deeper discussions around FMOD, where my programming and composition backgrounds intersected. I contributed ideas around event structure, parameters, and reactive music design.

**[Sep 28] Halfway Review**  
One track received tougher feedback than expected, and my initial response was frustration. After reflection, I recognised the distinction between a piece being *good* and being *right* for the project. I reworked the idea, preserving what served the game and discarding what didn’t. The result was leaner, clearer, and more functional.

*(Track in question:)*
![[The Menagerie Draft.mp3]]

---

## Sprint 4 (Oct 5 - Oct 18)
### Vertical Slice - Part 1

**[Oct 5] Team Meeting**  
With the vertical slice underway, audio gained concrete scope and dependencies. I planned FMOD structure early (naming conventions, hierarchies, and parameter needs) to minimise friction later. I also increased communication with programmers outside the audio team, translating musical ideas into technical requirements via a shared asset sheet document.

**[Oct 12] Halfway Review**  
Time constraints forced prioritisation. Rather than spreading effort thin, I focused on the moments that mattered most. I spent significant time debugging FMOD and resolving integration issues. Acting as a creative–technical bridge reduced confusion and sped up progress, reinforcing my confidence in this hybrid role (it's also extremely fun!).

*(Adaptive music in FMOD:)*
![[FMOD Intensity Stems Demo.mov]]
![[FMOD Adapdive Combat Music Demo.mov]]

---

## Sprint 5 (Oct 19 - Nov 1)
### Vertical Slice - Part 2

**[Oct 19] In-Person Team Meeting**  
Meeting in person was a huge change of pace from working remotely: faster decisions, better energy, and more natural feedback. Reviewing the near-final vertical slice, the project finally felt like it has legs from an audio perspective, and getting to see all the different facets integrated together benefitted everyone immensely - another game dev lesson I will certainly keep with me.

This sprint clarified my professional identity. I’m not just there to contribute audio assets - it's a role which requires collaboration, problem-solving, and connecting creative intent with technical execution. Across the project, I’ve grown more comfortable handling feedback, navigating creative disagreements, and working within a multidisciplinary team. The experience has been demanding at times, but overwhelmingly valuable, leaving me far better prepared for professional game development. 

